00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
It's if you think of an expression as a recipe, then the operations would be the steps, and

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:07.180
the functions and methods would be the cooks.

00:00:07.180 --> 00:00:12.900
So how does this metaphor shape your philosophy about best practices with data transformation

00:00:12.900 --> 00:00:17.959
design in order to deliver clean, readable pipelines, especially in large collaborative

00:00:17.959 --> 00:00:18.959
projects?

00:00:18.959 --> 00:00:21.440
The short answer is no more brackets.

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:23.799
With Polars, you take a different approach.

00:00:23.799 --> 00:00:26.639
You're writing a paragraph of things that you want to do.

00:00:26.639 --> 00:00:31.080
Yeah, and I think one of the things I've always liked most about Polars is the very

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:33.160
declarative approach of what you're writing down.

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:37.840
With Polars, you declare what you want as end result, and you just leave the specific

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:45.799
processing and optimization to the engine, and that makes it way easier to read.

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:49.720
