00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:45.360
So to start off with a little more context is that NVIDIA has a team called Rapids, which

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:52.280
is working on creating all kinds of general purpose computing packages that can run on

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:53.280
the CUDA platform.

00:52:53.280 --> 00:52:58.040
And CUDA is like the platform, calculation platform that NVIDIA opens up.

00:52:58.040 --> 00:53:02.719
So you can run any kind of calculation effectively on the GPU.

00:53:02.719 --> 00:53:07.919
And the difference between normal CPU and GPU is that GPU has many relatively dumb,

00:53:07.919 --> 00:53:10.540
simple processors, but just many of them.

00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:18.979
So if you're able to bend a calculation problem into something that the GPU can run, it oftentimes

00:53:18.979 --> 00:53:23.580
accelerates by a lot, by a factor up to 10.

00:53:23.580 --> 00:53:27.459
So they also did this for packages like Pandas.

00:53:27.459 --> 00:53:30.780
They have CUDEF, is what their package is called.

00:53:30.780 --> 00:53:33.860
It's a data frame library, but runs on the GPU.

00:53:33.860 --> 00:53:37.979
And they wanted to collaborate with Polars as well.

00:53:37.979 --> 00:53:45.040
But since Polars has this layered architecture where it runs through an optimizer first and

00:53:45.040 --> 00:53:51.340
only then gets sent to an engine, it would be a waste to just put the Polars API on CUDEF

00:53:51.340 --> 00:53:55.100
and just translate it to normal CUDEF functions, because a lot of the performance enhancements

00:53:55.100 --> 00:53:58.000
from Polars comes from this optimization.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:02.979
So instead, Rapids worked together with Polars and designed a GPU engine that gets input

00:54:02.979 --> 00:54:05.820
from that optimization layer.

00:54:06.459 --> 00:54:13.500
Because they recently finished the open beta for this new package, they got in contact

00:54:13.500 --> 00:54:18.219
with us to ask, hey, you guys are working on the book of Polars, do you want to collaborate?

00:54:18.219 --> 00:54:23.459
And we said, well, with the terms that we could test stuff ourselves and benchmark ourselves,

00:54:23.459 --> 00:54:28.620
we definitely said yes, because it turned out to be a lovely collaboration as well.

00:54:28.620 --> 00:54:29.620
That's a cool story.

